Laurent Bossavit wrote:
>
>> If your argument were accepted, no Judgement that the clear
>> meaning of the text of a Rule is contrary to game custom could ever
>> survive Appeal, for on your view, the mere fact of Appeal
>> establishes unclarity, and hence the primacy of game custom.
>
>Not the mere fact of Appeal, but the fact that the controversy 
>centers on the meaning of the Rule. But I'll grant your point.

OK, but you should realize the significance of this concession. The two
objections I raised to your proto-Judgement are not completely
independent of each other. If you concede that lee was entitled to view
the Rule as having a clear meaning contrary to game custom, then you
must accept that lee was entitled to disregard game custom in reaching
his Judgement. The entire weight of your disagreement with lee then
comes to rest on the question of whether lee's interpretation of Rule
1808 was correct, and not on the question of game custom.

I also want to add that even the existence of a controversy about the
meaning of a Rule is not sufficient to guarantee that a Rule is unclear.
You have to enquire as the nature of the controversy. I would describe
the present case, for example, as one where the controversy has arisen
not because a Rule is unclear, but because the consequences of a
Judgement are considered to be unpalatable.

>> I disagree that "directly to X" differs *strongly* in meaning to
>> "to X only". I think they differ only weakly in meaning. In
>> particular, "to X only" *implies* "directly to X", since sending
>> something indirectly to X only would involve sending it to someone
>> else, violating the requirement that the message be sent to X only.
>
>Not true. When I send mail to you, it passes through several relays
>before reaching you. If I wanted to add one more relay, that would
>make the submission of email from me to you less direct, but not
>necessarily less exclusive. 

I think this way of thinking about the possible meaning of 'direct' is
unhelpful, even wrong. I think we have to deny that the addition of one
more relay between A and B would make A's submission to B any less
direct, in the sense of 'direct' which ought to be at issue. Otherwise
we risk denying that any message is ever sent directly unless it passes
from A to B without any intervening relays at all, a condition that will
rarely if ever be met by messages being transmitted on the Internet.
Such a candidate interpretation of 'directly' is one of those which I
think lee was correct to exclude in his considerations. It's not close
enough to being reasonable in the context to make the word ambiguous or
unclear.

>Conversely, it is conceivable that a more direct way of reaching you
>might be less exclusive; for instance, if I left a message on your
>answering machine, and your roommate got it first, that message would
>be invalid as a Voting message. 

I disagree with this claim also. R1859 requires that the message be
*sent* to the Vote Collector only, not that it be received by the Vote
Collector only. If other persons end up reading a voting message which
was not sent to them, then that will not affect the validity of the
message according to R1859.

>I'm assuming this is 'more direct' in some sense. The term 'direct' in
>the context of Internet email is certainly a shifty one, and one more
>reason to argue that its addition to a Rule should not be allowed to
>change the substantial meaning of that Rule. 

But why use a problematic interpretation of 'directly' in terms of the
number of relays between sender and receiver, when lee's perfectly good
alternative interpretation in terms of number of recipients is
available, and does not lead to such subtle and shifty problems?

>In any case, I stand by my contention that "directly to X" and "only to
>X" are essentially orthogonal. 

And I stand by my contention that they are related by logical
implication: the latter implies the former.

