Laurent Bossavit writes:
> > The current Agoran ruleset does a pretty good job of controlling
> > our behaviour.  If we set up AgoraMOO, then the ruleset would
> > control the behaviour of the person implementing it to greater or
> > lesser extent and this would be control of the physics by the
> > rules. 
 
> As far as I can see, the same problem applies to Shattered residents ,
> and they seem to be dealing with it fine.

Huh?  Shattered World residents don't have any control over the
Wizards, and thus no control over the physics.  This contrasts with
our control of a system like AgoraMOO.
 
> > No, no, and no again.  It is the whole point of what Scott, Steve,
> > Blob and I are proposing that the rules *not* attempt to control
> > the people who control the MUD (i.e., the wizards).  Rather, the
> > rules should attempt to control the behaviour of the Players
> > *only*. Enforcement of those rules will definitely be an
> > interesting challenge, but these rules will only constrain Player
> > behaviour; not how objects should work in the world. 
 
> I'm not saying anything else. My point is that the hierarchy of
> power in AgoraMOO is occupied by persons already loyal to Agora,
> thus our enforcement is bound to be more effective. This doesn't
> imply any attempt at controlling the wizard's actions. It will
> simply be the case that the players charged with enforcement (city
> guards, whatever) can be recruited from the ranks of Agora.
   
OK, I agree that the task of setting up the world for our use would be
easier in AgoraMOO.  I don't understand your last comment about
enforcement though.  If we actually wanted humans to be city guards
(as opposed to robots), then we could get Agorans to do this whether
or not we were playing in AgoraMOO or SW.

> > This is true.  If you manage to attract a reasonable set of people to
> > play the MOO who are not players in Agora, then you may even be in a
> > position to implement something like my Polis proposal.  
 
> What's that ?
 
This is my suggestion that we set up a MUD and take on the role of
Gods, not Players.  We'd still have a physical world to play with, but
it would make sense for us to be able to control it.  The problem with
this is that it really requires us to go out there and recruit players
for the MUD.   (I've attached my proto from way back when.)

Michael.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
              *** Polis (or the Agora sub-universe) ***

Let a rule be created with the title "Polis and the Strategos" and the
following text:

As soon as practically possible, there shall be created a MUD-like
implementation of a "world", open to the general Internet public.
This world shall be known as "Polis", and will be the collective
responsibility of the Players of Agora.  However, the day to day
maintenance and development of Polis will be the responsibility of a
new elected Officer, the Strategos.

Further rules will dictate characteristics of Polis, but insofar as
the rules do not constrain them, the Strategos is free to implement
Polis as they see fit.  The Strategos necessarily must have access to
a suitable computer to serve as the site for the Polis MUD.

Players in the Polis MUD are to be known henceforth as Mortals.

--------------------

Let a rule be created with the title "Duties of the Strategos" and the
following text:

The Strategos shall implement and maintain the Polis MUD system.  The
Strategos is responsible for both the day-to-day running of the MUD,
and also for changes to the implementation required by changes to
Agoran Law.  The Strategos may be made responsible for other duties
relating to Polis by other rules.

The Strategos must maintain a log of their actions, and must make a
Report of their activities every week.

--------------------

Let a rule be created with the title "Access to Polis" and the
following text:

In general, anyone capable of it must be allowed to connect to Polis
and become a Mortal.  Agora Players may also become Mortals, but must
report both the fact that they are doing so, and the name under which
they are doing so, to the Strategos.  Further, the Strategos is given
leave to ban and/or expel Mortals who, in the Strategos' judgement,
are endangering the long-term technical viability of the MUD system,
or who are acting in a persistently obnoxious fashion.  These
decisions are necessarily subject to Judicial Review within the usual
Agoran channels.

--------------------

Let a rule be created with the title "Polis in abeyance" and the
following text:

For various reasons (such as loss of access to the hosting site for
the Polis MUD), it may occasionally become necessary for Polis to be
put in abeyance or discontinued.  If this happens, the Strategos is
responsible for preservation of as much of the state of Polis as
possible, and for the speedy resurrection of the game afterwards.

All rules governing aspects of Polis only do so when Polis is active;
when in abeyance Polis is static and by default not subject to rules
about Polis.  This condition defers only to those Rules that
explicitly seek to override it.

--------------------




