Laurent Bossavit writes:

>>> The Gods of Shattered World happen to be SW resident. I should
>>> know, I'm speaking with one at this moment, getting him to fix
>>> some physics.
 
>> Yeah, sure, but they are not normal residents.  I think Agoran
>> players should be normal residents of their MUD, not Gods.
 
> How do you mean, not normal ? They're normal, apart from being
> Gods... :) AFAIK even the higher levels have to eat etc. Most of
> them appear to have several characters, secondaries with lesser
> powers, though. But note that one is essentially a God by virtue of
> having access to the server in an administrative function; this does
> not necessarily prevent the characters 'incarnating' the Gods from
> being subject to (most of) the same laws as mere mortals.

The problem in AgoraMOO is that by allowing abnormal Players (i.e.,
those have a humans behind them that have wizardly powers in the MUD),
is that Agora then has untoward influence on the physics of the game.
Those characters that have Gods behind them may well be subject to the
normal physics of the game, but the God like powers they have
(indirectly) may well result in adjustments to the physics that we
shouldn't be able to make. 

Specifically, if you are an Engineer or something for AgoraMOO, then a
faction of sufficiently motivated Players might decide that they
wanted to be able to fly.  They pass a law to that effect, and
suddenly, you as an Agoran player are required to implement it.  For
one thing, that's a hassle for you, and two, it makes a mockery of the
idea of the ruleset being embodied in a reality because the ruleset
is patently able to reach outside itself and fiddle with physics. 

I admit that in Shattered World, we would still need to enshrine
(perhaps as a very high Power rule) the principle that rules governing
the behaviour of characters in the MUD should not seek to govern the
behaviour of the people behind them.  Otherwise, we could pass rules
saying "If a Mortal whose controlling person is also a God should
enter Merenth, then that player must use their Godly powers to give
all Agoran Mortals 100 gold pieces."

And yes, the obvious corollary is that we could set up a similar rule
for AgoraMOO (something along the lines of "No rule shall attempt to
prescribe the behaviour of the Engineer"), but then, there are other
advantages to SW: it has lots of other players, an existing physics
and an economy as well.  AgoraMOO has none of these things, and I
believe that they are all quite difficult to get. 

Michael.


