> I think that should be a guiding principle.  It is sufficiently
> constrictive to make life interesting.  Besides, i don't think the
> Engineer would listen unless e felt like it.  The chief thing wrong
> in the Polis agreement is that it does require the Engineer to do
> things.
 
If the Engineer were a Player of Agora, then they'd have to follow the
rules (check R101), so they'd need the protection of a high power rule
such as the one I propose.

> I'm not giving up on AgoraMOO, I don't see being a programmer as
> being all that god like.  I can create stuff, with work.  It puts me
> in a different class than simple players, but doesn't take me
> outside of the physics of the world.  I like it there, and i think
> it will be fun shaping a new world.  I don't find SW rewarding at
> all, and i'm not investing any more time there.  I hope other
> Agorans will work on AgoraMOO.
 
There's no point to working on AgoraMOO communally unless there is
some general idea about where we'd want to take it.  Have you got an
idea about the general physics of the game?  Have you figured out some
form of conflict resolution (combat, say)?  What happens to a
character if they're killed/toaded etc?  Shouldn't there be some sort
of restriction on people's abilities to build things; (resources *are*
finite, right)?  If I build things, do I need to go and get building
materials first?  If I build things, should other people be able to
destroy them? (*)

AgoraMOO needs to be more than the "gimmicky chat room" of something
like LambdaMOO if it is to be of any interest from the nomic (ruleset)
perspective.  It might well turn into a cool place to socialise for
Agoran members, but it will be legislatively dull.

Michael
(*) These questions are not necessarily answered well in SW, but of
    course, in AgoraMOO you are in a position to answer them even
    better because you are doing everything from scratch. 

