The builder systems definitely have something compared to the LP-like
systems in this respect.  (I don't think normal players on SW are able
to build anything at all.) However, as it stands, there's not much for
our rules to grab hold of in such a system.  So let's think: what sort
of economy do we have here?

Clearly people can create added value by creating things that other
Players desire.  However, the issue of ownership doesn't seem clear.
Only the creator of an object can destroy it, and object creators can
only create a finite number of objects.  Real estate is another form
of object, so subject to the same sort of problems. 

Second question: how can your objects affect other Players?  
 
> I hope we will legislate a better system than combat in order to
> settle disputes.  I think the legislation of the MOO should be
> separate from the rules, but of course Players are always subject to
> the Rules.

Combat is a very interesting dispute resolution method.  It certainly
has its flaws, but it would be interesting to legislate for.  It also
has the virtue of perhaps giving the game a little extra spice. 

Can AgoraMOO implement differing coinage systems easily? 

Michael.

