Laurent Bossavit wrote:
>
>> Your second example ("I hereby delegate the Office of Assessor to
>> whomever is willing to take it.") is, at least potentially, an
>> example of failure to be specific (if there is more than one
>> willing Delegate), but where is the evidence that game custom has
>> ever allowed this statement on its own to constitute a Notice of
>> Delegation? 
>
>Ask the Archivist, not me. I remember several instances. I may also
>add that "I Delegate to X, if willing", which you will certainly
>remember has been used frequently, can be considered to 'specify' an
>entity which may or may not exist, depending on whether X is willing
>or not. It has always irked me somewhat that we are willing to allow
>such vague designations when the Rules ask for a successor to be
>'specified', just as it annoys Kolja to see Rule 1567 used in that
>way. I just don't feel like sustaining a Judgement where a decision
>is not only at odds with game custom but based on personal preference
>and nothing else.

I think is a poor example to be discussing in connection with CFJ 1101.
R1645 nowhere uses the word 'specific'. Here's what it does say:

      An Office is legally Delegated if and only if the following
      conditions are met:

      (i)   the Delegating Player has posted to the Public Forum a
      Notice of Delegation, naming the Office being Delegated and the
      Delegated Player;

As you can see, what R1645 requires is that the Player be named. So "I
delegate the Office of Assessor to Chuck, if he is willing" is fine as a
Notice of Delegation, provided that we're prepared to accept the use of
the conditional. But our acceptance of (some) conditional actions is a
completely separate issue from that of vagueness or ambiguity in
specification, and the two issues should not be confused.


-- 


